#: ../../noir.rst:-1
msgid "Compile Noir zero-knowledge circuits in Remix IDE, generate ZK proofs, and verify them using Solidity smart contracts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:-1
msgid "noir compiler, zero knowledge, zk proof, remix ide, noir zkp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:2
msgid "Noir Compiler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:8
msgid "Noir lets you build zero-knowledge applications without writing cryptographic circuits. This guide covers the entire workflow of using the Noir Compiler plugin in Remix IDE to compile Noir code, generate a zero-knowledge proof, and verify the generated proof using a Solidity smart contract and a js script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:11
msgid "Creating a Noir Workspace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:13
msgid "To create a Noir template, click the **\"Create a new workspace\"** button in the top center of the screen and scroll to find the **\"Noir ZKP\"** template and click **\"Create\"**. This will create a new workspace with the necessary ``Nargo.toml`` and ``src/main.nr`` files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:25
msgid "After generating the workspace, the Noir Compiler Plugin will automatically be activated and the icon will appear on the Icon Panel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:28
msgid "Compiling Noir circuits"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:30
msgid "Selecting the ``main.nr`` file will activate the **\"Compile\"** button. When you click the button the plugin starts the compilation process by zipping the project files and sending them to the compiler's backend. On the backend, the server runs ``nargo compile`` and on successful compilation creates/overwrites two files in your workspace:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:33
msgid "``build/program.json``: The compiled circuit artifact (ACIR/ABI)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:34
msgid "``Prover.toml``: A template file for providing inputs needed for proof generation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:36
msgid "Once the compilation process is complete, a **\"Compilation Artifacts\"** section appears on the Noir Compiler Plugin page showing a **\"View Artifact\"** button. The **\"Generate Proof\"** button is activated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:38
msgid "If a compilation error occurs during this process, the error message will be displayed in the feedback window below the **\"Compile\"** button."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:52
msgid "Setting circuit inputs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:53
msgid "If your circuit requires inputs (private or public), you must edit the ``Prover.toml`` file before generating a proof. In the file, fill in the required input values in the ``[inputs]`` section and save the file (e.g., ``a = \"1\"``, ``b = \"2\"``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:67
msgid "Generating zero-knowledge proofs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:69
msgid "Once the inputs are set, click the **\"Generate Proof\"** button. Similar to the compilation process, the plugin zips the entire project, including the ``Prover.toml``, and sends it to the backend. The backend runs ``nargo execute`` to generate a witness, then uses the proving library (bb.js) to generate the proof and related artifacts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:72
msgid "The plugin receives a zip file and extracts the following files into your workspace:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:73
msgid "``build/proof``: The formatted hexadecimal proof for use in UI and Solidity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:74
msgid "``build/public_inputs``: The formatted JSON array of public inputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:75
msgid "``contracts/Verifier.sol``: A Solidity smart contract for verifying the proof."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:76
msgid "``scripts/verify.ts``: A JS script for verifying the proof in Remix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:78
msgid "On the plugin UI, the **\"Proof Artifacts\"** section appears along with buttons to view the four main generated files (\"View Proof\", \"View Public Inputs\", \"View Verifier.sol\", \"View verify.ts\")."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:83
msgid "Verifying proofs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:85
msgid "Once the proof is generated, you can verify it in two ways."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:89
msgid "On-Chain verification (with Solidity)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:90
msgid "Follow the steps below to verify your proof on-chain using Solidity:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:92
msgid "In the Noir plugin, click **\"View Verifier.sol\"** to open the verifier contract."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:93
msgid "Go to the **\"Solidity Compiler\"** plugin in Remix, open **\"Advanced Configurations\"**, and check **\"Enable optimization\"**. Compile ``Verifier.sol``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:94
msgid "Go to the **\"Deploy & Run Transactions\"** plugin and deploy the ``HonkVerifier`` contract."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:95
msgid "Find the ``verify`` function on the deployed contract."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:96
msgid "Go back to the Noir plugin, click **\"View Proof\"**, and copy the entire ``0x...`` hexadecimal string. Paste it into the ``_proof`` parameter of the ``verify`` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:97
msgid "Click **\"View Public Inputs\"**, copy the entire ``[\"0x...\", ...]`` JSON array string, and paste it into the ``_publicInputs`` parameter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:98
msgid "Execute the ``verify`` transaction (call). If it returns ``true``, the verification is successful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:111
msgid "Off-Chain verification (with JS Script)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:112
msgid "Follow the steps below to verify your proof off-chain using JavaScript:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:114
msgid "In the Noir plugin, click **\"View verify.ts\"** to open the verification script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:115
msgid "Click the **dropdown arrow** next to the **\"Run script\"** button in the editor's top bar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:116
msgid "Select **\"Open script configuration\"** from the menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:117
msgid "In the configuration panel or modal, set the **\"Execution environment\"** to **\"Noir\"**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../noir.rst:118
msgid "Close the configuration window and click the main **\"Run script\"** button to execute the script."
msgstr ""
